beer_description: Microbrewery

Over 12 months in whiskey barrels has completely transformed our prized winter seasonal, producing a Hibernation that starts with big whiskey flavors before mellowing out into luscious chocolate, dark fruit and vanilla.  If you can only take one beer into your cave this winter, we suggest this one.

beer_description: This special release of our acclaimed, hefty barley wine has been aged for over 12 months whiskey barrels.  The process tempers Old Ruffian?s edges for a mellowed version with heady whiskey flavors and subtle oak notes. This rounded wonder clocks in at 85-90 IBUs.

This original Leipzig beer specialty lends us the name for our brewery. Gose is a regional beer specialty that was brought to Saxony-Anhalt in the year 1738. Originally Gose comes from Goslar, a small town in Lower Saxony, and the river ?Gose? in this town. This beer specialty has a refreshing, slightly sour taste and is ideal for quenching your thirst. Gose is brewed with the additional ingredients lactic acid, cilantro, and salt. Gose is a top-fermented beer with  4,6 Vol. % alcohol and 10,8 % wort. You can enjoy it in different variations.

Introduced New Year's Eve 1999 as our salute to the year 2000. Barley wine is a style of beer referred to as wine because of the high alcohol content (in this case 10.5%). Our barley wine is a nicely balanced beer made with three kinds of malts and bittered with Cascade hops (This barley wine is sometimes aged in a "Single-Barrell" Jack Daniels whiskey barrell. check the chalkboard at the pub to see if Whiskey Barrell Barley Wine is on tap when you visit us.

Our strongest ale with 10.6% alcohol by weight. Brilliant amber in color, aromas laden with alcohol and the fruity bouquet of sweet malt, warming alcohols, and ample hop flavors. It is a beer to be sipped, contemplated, and relished as one would a fine Port or Sherry.

This is our first really strong ale brewed and the beginning of our entry into the Barleywine festivals such as is held at the Toronado pub in San Francisco annually every end of February. It was also our 500th batch of beer brew so we figured we were due to brew a strong beer like this by now. It was brewed on 8/30/99 and had an S. G. of 1.080 and a F.G. of 1.014 for and a.b.v. of 8.8%

The appeal of the tasteful label is continued with the beautiful rich copper amber color of this special beer. It is brewed for Easter and is predominantly a mellow malt with some citric hop character. It is a very good beer that certainly improves for up to two years but somehow doesn?t quite live up to the "special" status. It is sold as 1549 in the USA.

Big Bear is a big, black, stout you can really sink your teeth into. The bold, roasty, caramel malt flavor is balanced by Centennial and Cascade hops.

beer_description:
Tasting Notes:
The Emperor of Stouts. Rich in texture, broad, soft and creamy. The most robust and fullest of all stouts.
 
15 Ingredients:
Malts: Crystal, Black, Chocolate, Great Western 2-Row Malts & Rolled Oats. Hops: Chinook, Perle, Cascade. Specialty: Two Secret ingredients. Yeast & Water: Rogue's Proprietary Pacman Yeast & Free Range Coastal Water

Food Pairing: Beef, Desserts

HISTORY
Imperial Stout, also known as ?Russian Imperial Stout? is a variety of ale that was originally brewed in England for export to the court of the Tsar of Russia. Its high level of hopping is intended to preserve it during long trips and to provide a more bracing drink against cold climates. The colour is very dark, nearly opaque black. Imperial stout exhibits enormously powerful malt flavours, hints of dark fruits, and is often quite dry.

?He was a wise man who invented beer.?
- Plato
Made in North Yorkshire, England UK, 7.0%

Piney, citrus hop notes combine with rich roast and alcohol heat. Flavor is full of complexity from a heavy hop addition and a rich grain bill. Espresso, bitter chocolate, grapefruit rind, and earth hot character. Bitter finish.
Imperial Stout is patterned after the highly fortified Russian Stouts that were exported from the U.K. to Russia in the 1800s.

First in the Old Ales/Strong Milds category of the 25th Cambridge Beer Festival, Atom Splitter is a beer with plenty of character, bursting with First Gold hoppiness. Atom Splitter has an ABV of 4.5%.

The History


Cambridge has a long association with research into the nature of the atom. The Cavendish Laboratory is a world leading research centre into atomic and nuclear physics. Established in 1874 under the guidance of James Clerk Maxwell the Cavendish laboratory has had many notable researchers as students and also staff. JJ Thomson, who discovered the electron, was a Cavendish Professor. A small plaque in Free School Lane commemorates the discovery. Thomson?s students included Ernest Rutherford, who discovered nuclear fission, and Charles Wilson, who invented the cloud chamber.

1997 Champion Beer, Cambridge Beer Festival. Finalist 1998 Great British Beer Festival at Olympia. Bronze Award 1999 Beauty of Hops English Ale Awards. A light golden bitter with a pronounced hop aroma, contributing to the refreshing bitter aftertaste. Hobsons Choice has an ABV of 4.1%.

The History
Named after Thomas Hobson Esq a Cambridge carrier who delivered mail between London and Cambridge. The stables were near St Catherine?s College in the centre of the city and when the horses were not delivering mail they were used by the students and staff of the university. Thomas Hobson noticed that the strongest and fastest horses were very popular and tended to be overworked. He devised a scheme whereby customers were offered the choice of the horse nearest to the door or none at all, renting his horses out in strict rotation. Hence there was no choice at all.
Pheasant Pluckers

We mashed up traditional English-style barley wine-style and old ale winter warmer-style ales with citrusy American hops like Simcoe, Centennial, Columbus, Chinook, Amarillo and, fittingly, Glacier, to create a Floridian Winter Ale.
